===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|desdeignier}} (modern French {{m|fr|dédaigner}}).

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|dĭs-dān'}}, {{IPA|/dɪsˈdeɪn/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|eɪn|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-}}

# {{lb|en|uncountable}} A [[feeling]] of [[contempt]] or [[scorn]].
#: ''The cat viewed the cheap supermarket catfood with '''disdain''' and stalked away.''
#* William Shakespeare, ''Much ado about Nothing'':
#*: '''Disdain''' and scorn ride sparkling in her eyes.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} That which is [[worthy]] to be disdained or regarded with contempt and [[aversion]].
#* Spenser
#*: Most loathsome, filthy, foul, and full of vile '''disdain'''.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} The state of being despised; shame.
#: {{rfquotek|Shakespeare}}

